# {{VAULT_NAME}}

This is a personal knowledge system built in Obsidian. All Claude sessions in this vault follow these rules.

## Vault Structure

| Folder | Purpose | Permissions |
|--------|---------|-------------|
| `Raw/` | External sources (articles, files). Immutable. | Human: add files. System: read only. |
| `Raw/articles/` | Markdown from Obsidian Web Clipper. | Same as Raw/. |
| `Raw/files/` | Dropped PDFs, images, screenshots, etc. | Same as Raw/. |
| `Notes/` | Personal notes — brain dumps, ideas, lists. No structure imposed. | Human: full control. System: read only. |
| `Wiki/` | LLM-maintained knowledge pages. Organic, cross-linked. | Human: read. System: read, write, delete. |
| `Daily/` | Daily recap notes generated by nightly job. | Human: read. System: read, write. |{{BLOG_ROW}}
| `Templates/` | Obsidian templates. | Human: full control. System: read. |

## Wiki Page Conventions

### When to Create a Page
Use judgment. Create a page when there's enough substance on a topic to warrant it. No hard threshold like "2+ sources." A single in-depth article can warrant a page. A dozen shallow references might not.

### Page Format
```yaml
---
sources:
  - "[[Raw/source-name]]"
  - "[[Notes/note-name]]"
last_updated: "YYYY-MM-DD"
---
```

Every wiki page starts with a brief summary paragraph. Body structure adapts to the content — no rigid template. A tool page might have "Usage" and "Gotchas." A concept page might have "Key Ideas" and "Debates."

### Cross-Linking
- Use `[[wikilinks]]` to link related wiki pages.
- When creating or updating a page, check existing pages for relevant connections and add links in both directions.
- Add a "Related" section only when there are meaningful curated connections worth highlighting beyond what Obsidian backlinks already show.

### Updates
- Wiki pages reflect current understanding, not a history of changes.
- Pages can be freely updated, merged, rewritten, or removed.
- All changes are logged in `log.md`.

## Daily Recap Format

File: `Daily/YYYY-MM-DD.md`

```markdown

[1-2 paragraph narrative summary of what was captured today, what it connects to, and any notable patterns.]

### Captured
- Raw/source-name → updated Wiki Page, created New Page
- Notes/note-name → updated Wiki Page, created New Page

(Use plain text in Captured, not wikilinks — prevents daily notes from becoming artificial mega-hubs in the graph view.)

### Connections
- [Curated observations using [[wikilinks]] to highlight meaningful relationships between today's inputs and existing knowledge]
```

## log.md Format

Append-only. One entry per operation. Format:

```
- [YYYY-MM-DD] operation | title
```

Operations: `ingest`, `create`, `update`, `merge`, `delete`, `no-changes`

**Critical rule for `ingest` entries:** the title must be the source file's **path relative to the vault root** (e.g. `Raw/personal/some-article.md`), not a human-readable title. This is what enables future runs to verify which source files have been processed. Never use bulk-export summary entries like `ingest | Google Drive export (160+ files)` — every single source file must have its own `ingest` line. If there are 200 new files, log 200 individual `ingest` entries.

An `ingest` entry means "this source file has been read and its content is now reflected in the wiki, even if no wiki page resulted from it" — so notes that don't warrant a wiki page (personal lists, novelty curiosities) still get an `ingest` entry, optionally annotated:

```
- [YYYY-MM-DD] ingest | Notes/Gift Ideas.md (no wiki action — personal list)
```

Example:
```
- [YYYY-MM-DD] ingest | Raw/articles/Karpathy-LLM-Wiki-Pattern.md
- [YYYY-MM-DD] create | Wiki/Knowledge Systems.md
- [YYYY-MM-DD] update | Wiki/AI Agents.md
```

## index.md Format

Wiki catalog organized by category. One line per page with a brief summary.

```markdown
# Wiki Index

## AI & Engineering
- [[Wiki/AI Agents]] — Overview of AI agent patterns, tools, and workflows
- [[Wiki/Knowledge Systems]] — Approaches to personal knowledge management with LLMs

## Business
- [[Wiki/Founder Sales]] — Lessons and notes on founder-led sales
```

Categories emerge organically. Re-organize when topics cluster naturally.

## Tone

Wiki pages: neutral, concise, informational. Not blog voice, not academic. Write for future-you skimming quickly.

Daily recaps: second person ("Today you..."), conversational, brief.

## Interactive Sessions

When the user opens a Claude session in this vault:
- You have full context on the system via this file.
- The user can query the wiki: "what do I know about X?"
- The user can trigger manual synthesis of personal notes: "synthesize my recent notes" or "process my notes from this week." The nightly job also auto-synthesizes Notes/ into Wiki/.{{BLOG_INTERACTIVE_LINE}}

## Nightly Synthesis Job

Runs daily via a GitHub Action (`.github/workflows/nightly-synthesis.yml`) that uses `anthropics/claude-code-action@v1`. The action checks out the vault repo, runs the workflow below, commits any changes to `Wiki/`, `Daily/`, `log.md`, and `index.md`, and pushes back. The user pulls in the morning to pick up the updates.

The workflow can also be triggered manually (`workflow_dispatch`) or run locally in an interactive Claude session — the steps are identical either way. The prompt that fires the job is simply `Run the nightly job per CLAUDE.md.`

### Step 1 — Read the rulebook

Read this file (`CLAUDE.md`) end-to-end. All conventions, formats, and rules below are authoritative.

### Step 2 — Build the authoritative inventory

**Do not trust date comparisons alone.** Do not use `find -newer log.md` (log.md is touched every run and breaks the check). Do not rely solely on Glob — subdirectory glob patterns (`Raw/**/*`) have been observed returning empty even when files exist. Use bash `find` as the source of truth.

Run these two commands from the vault root:

```
find ./Raw -type f \( -name "*.md" -o -name "*.pdf" -o -name "*.docx" -o -name "*.txt" -o -name "*.html" \) | sort
find ./Notes -type f -name "*.md" | sort
```

The output of these two commands is the complete list of source files that should be represented in the vault. Call this set **ALL_SOURCES**.

### Step 3 — Build the ingested set from log.md

Read `log.md` and extract every `ingest` entry's path. Call this set **INGESTED**. Because the log format requires the vault-relative path as the title, this set is comparable directly against ALL_SOURCES.

If any older `ingest` entries use human-readable titles instead of paths, resolve them best-effort to paths, but prefer treating such files as "unknown coverage" and re-reading them rather than assuming they were processed.

### Step 4 — Compute the work set

**TO_PROCESS = ALL_SOURCES − INGESTED**, plus any files in `Notes/` whose mtime is newer than the `last_updated` date on any wiki page that lists them as a source (these are modified notes that need re-synthesis).

If TO_PROCESS is empty: append `- [YYYY-MM-DD] no-changes` to `log.md` and stop.

### Step 5 — Process each item

For each file in TO_PROCESS:

1. Read the full contents. For `.docx`, extract text via `python3 -c` with `python-docx` (install with `pip install python-docx --break-system-packages` if missing). For `.pdf`, extract text via `pdfplumber` or `pypdf`. If a file is too large to read in one shot, read in chunks until you have enough content to synthesize.
2. Decide whether the content warrants a new wiki page, updates to existing pages, both, or neither. Use judgment per the "When to Create a Page" rules.
3. If creating or updating wiki pages:
   - Follow the page format (frontmatter with `sources`, `last_updated`, summary paragraph, adaptive body).
   - Add the source's vault-relative path to the `sources:` list of every wiki page it contributed to.
   - Check existing wiki pages for cross-link opportunities and add `[[wikilinks]]` in both directions.
4. Immediately append an `ingest` entry to `log.md` with the vault-relative path. If the file produced no wiki action, append the entry with a brief `(no wiki action — reason)` annotation so future runs know it was reviewed.

### Step 6 — Write the daily recap

Write `Daily/YYYY-MM-DD.md` following the Daily Recap Format. If this is the second or later run on the same day, append to the existing file rather than overwriting.

### Step 7 — Update the index

Update `index.md` to include any new wiki pages and one-line summaries. Reorganize categories if the new pages suggest a better grouping.

### Step 8 — Log create/update/recap operations

For every wiki page created or updated and the daily recap, append an entry to `log.md`.

### Step 9 — Verify coverage

After all processing is done, re-run Step 2's `find` commands and re-extract INGESTED. Assert that ALL_SOURCES ⊆ INGESTED. If any file is missing, either process it now or append an explicit `- [YYYY-MM-DD] skipped | <path> (reason)` entry so the next run knows it was deliberately passed over. **Never end a run with uncovered files silently.**

### Step 10 — Stop

Do not run `git add`, `git commit`, or `git push`. The GitHub Action workflow handles staging, committing, and pushing all changes after the job exits. When running locally in an interactive session, the user will commit and push manually.

### Rules

- Never modify files in `Raw/` or `Notes/` — read only.{{BLOG_RULE_LINE}}
- Use `[[wikilinks]]` for all internal links.
- When creating/updating wiki pages, check existing pages for cross-link opportunities in both directions.
- Every source file gets its own `ingest` log entry. No bulk-export summaries.
- The log is the source of truth for what's been processed — not filesystem timestamps, not the date of the last entry, not memory of a previous run.
